The virus infection can be provisionally diagnosed on the basis of symptoms, although ultimately it is confirmed through the reverse transcriptase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) of infected secretions or through computed tomography images.
According to a study in Wuhan comparing polymerase chain reaction with computed tomography, computed tomography is much more sensitive than polymerase chain reaction, although less specific, and many of the characteristics in images match the processes of other diseases and pneumonia.
Since March 2020, the American College of Radiology recommends "not using computed tomography as a method of detection or as a front-line test to diagnose the COVID-19".
